    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "6&ndash;9",
      "detail": "4th in AL East &middot; 50th Anniversary Season &middot; Defending AL Champions",
      "live_strip": null,
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "Folks, the Blue Jays are scrapping their way through a brutal nine-games-in-nine-days road swing, banged up with a five-man rotation and four lineup regulars on the IL, yet showing real fight against slumping foes. <strong>They gutted out a wild extra-inning win over the Brewers last night</strong>, rallying with doubles from Vladimir Guerrero Jr. and Myles Straw to plate three in the top of the frame, while the pen&mdash;capped by Landon Varland's clutch three outs&mdash;held firm after Kevin Gausman's gritty five-inning, three-run start that wasn't his sharpest but bought time[1][4]. Sitting at 6-9 in the loaded AL East, they've snapped a skid and embraced this underdog identity amid MLB's second-worst offense with runners in scoring position[4][5]. Vlad's delivering in the clutch, Darin Varsho's raking from the two-hole, and Jacob Lopez looks solid in his fourth start at 3.31 ERA, but the staff's desperate for stability after coughing up 19 runs in 11.2 weekend frames[4][5]. Milwaukee's reeling without Christian Yelich's hot .314 start (now groin-IL'd), which helped Toronto steal one[4]. <strong>Up next: Dylan Cease takes the hill tonight against the Brewers</strong>&mdash;if the bats wake up, they could grab a series win before the trip drags west[2].",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
